recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain 2019-2020 230i, 230i xDrive, M240i, M240i xDrive, M2 Competition Coupe, 430i, 430i xDrive, 440i, 440i xDrive, M4, and 2019 330i xDrive Sportswagon vehicles.  The driver and passenger knee air bag assemblies may have been improperly folded and assembled.
recalls.Consequence: An improperly folded and assembled air bag may not deploy as intended, increasing risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will replace the knee air bag modules, free of charge.  The recall began July 8, 2019.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

issues.title: S55 Engine Crank Hub Failure
issues.description: The S55 engine's crank hub can fail catastrophically, causing the harmonic balancer to separate from the crankshaft, leading to complete engine failure and potential damage to surrounding components.
issues.fix_description: Replace crankshaft, harmonic balancer, and potentially rebuild entire engine depending on damage extent
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid excessive high RPM usage, monitor for unusual noises

issues.title: Fuel Injector Failure
issues.description: High-pressure fuel injectors on the S55 engine are prone to failure, causing misfires, rough idle, and poor performance. Multiple injectors often fail simultaneously.
issues.fix_description: Replace all fuel injectors and perform engine coding/adaptation
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, regular fuel system cleaning, avoid prolonged idling

issues.title: Charge Pipe Failure
issues.description: The plastic charge pipe connecting the intercooler to the intake manifold is prone to cracking or blowing off under boost pressure, causing sudden loss of power.
issues.fix_description: Replace with upgraded aluminum or reinforced plastic charge pipe
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of charge pipes, avoid aggressive tuning without supporting modifications

issues.title: DCT Transmission Jerky Shifting
issues.description: The 7-speed DCT transmission exhibits jerky or harsh shifting, particularly during low-speed maneuvers or in stop-and-go traffic.
issues.fix_description: Software update, transmission adaptation reset, or clutch replacement in severe cases
issues.prevention: Regular transmission fluid changes, proper warm-up procedures, avoid aggressive launches

issues.title: Carbon Build-up on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection engines accumulate carbon deposits on intake valves over time, reducing airflow and engine performance.
issues.fix_description: Walnut blasting or chemical cleaning of intake valves
issues.prevention: Regular highway driving, quality fuel usage, periodic intake cleaning services

issues.title: Cooling System Failure
issues.description: Water pump, thermostat, and cooling system components are prone to premature failure, leading to overheating and potential engine damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace water pump, thermostat, and associated cooling components
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, monitoring coolant levels, addressing leaks promptly

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: Internal wastegate components in the turbochargers develop excessive play, causing rattling noises and potential boost control issues.
issues.fix_description: Replace or rebuild turbochargers with updated wastegate components
issues.prevention: Allow proper turbo cool-down, use quality oil, regular maintenance

issues.title: Electronic Issues with iDrive System
issues.description: Various electronic glitches affecting the iDrive infotainment system, including frozen screens, connectivity issues, and system crashes.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, module replacement, or complete head unit replacement
issues.prevention: Keep software updated, avoid extreme temperatures, proper system shutdown

issues.title: Rear Differential Bushing Wear
issues.description: Rear differential bushings wear prematurely, causing clunking noises and vibrations, particularly during aggressive driving or launches.
issues.fix_description: Replace rear differential bushings with OEM or upgraded polyurethane bushings
issues.prevention: Avoid harsh launches, regular inspection, proper alignment

issues.title: Oil Filter Housing Gasket Leak
issues.description: The oil filter housing gasket develops leaks over time, causing oil to drip onto the exhaust and creating burning oil smell and potential fire hazard.
issues.fix_description: Replace oil filter housing gasket and clean affected areas
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, proper torque specifications, quality gaskets

editorial.tagline: Pure M Division precision in compact form
editorial.hero_blurb: The M2 Competition represents BMW's most focused performance offering, distilling decades of M Division expertise into a compact, track-ready package. With its S55 twin-turbo straight-six and razor-sharp chassis dynamics, it delivers an uncompromising driving experience that purists crave.
editorial.essence: The M2 Competition is BMW's last hurrah for the analog sports car experience, combining modern turbocharged power with traditional rear-wheel-drive dynamics. It's small enough to feel intimate yet powerful enough to thrill, representing the perfect balance between street usability and track capability.
editorial.heritage: Born from the legendary 2002 turbo lineage and carrying forward the compact M car tradition, the M2 Competition sits as the spiritual successor to the beloved E30 M3. It represents BMW's commitment to keeping the pure driving experience alive in an increasingly digital automotive world.
editorial.design_philosophy: Designers focused on functional aggression over flashy styling, creating purposeful aerodynamic elements that serve performance first. Every bulge, vent, and surface treatment exists to manage airflow, cooling, or enhance the car's planted stance.
editorial.motorsport_history: While newer to the M lineup, the M2 carries the DNA of decades of BMW motorsport success, incorporating lessons learned from touring car racing and track development programs into its chassis tuning and aerodynamic package.
editorial.engine_character: The S55 twin-turbo straight-six delivers instant, crushing torque with a linear power delivery that builds relentlessly to redline. It's refined yet aggressive, offering both daily drivability and track-day intensity with minimal turbo lag.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 7-speed DCT shifts with mechanical precision and lightning speed, offering seamless gear changes under full acceleration. Each shift feels deliberate and crisp, enhancing the car's aggressive character whether on track or street.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The chassis exhibits perfect balance between compliance and control, rotating naturally under throttle while remaining composed over rough surfaces. It's stiff enough for serious track work yet civilized enough for daily driving.
editorial.steering_feel: The steering provides excellent feedback and weighting, communicating road surface changes and grip levels clearly to the driver. It's quick enough for spirited driving without being twitchy, offering confidence-inspiring precision.
editorial.brake_confidence: The brakes deliver strong, consistent stopping power with excellent pedal feel and minimal fade under hard use. They inspire confidence whether scrubbing speed for a tight corner or hauling down from triple-digit speeds.
editorial.sound_signature: The exhaust produces a distinctive growl that's both refined and aggressive, with subtle pops and crackles on overrun. The turbo straight-six creates a unique sonic character that's unmistakably BMW M.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving enthusiasts who want maximum performance in a compact package, track day regulars who need a car that excels on circuit, and BMW purists seeking the last of the analog M car experience.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Buyers seeking maximum luxury, families needing rear seat space, or those wanting the flashiest sports car presence in the BMW lineup.
editorial.buyers_summary: The M2 Competition represents exceptional value in the performance car segment, offering supercar-level capability in a more accessible package. Look for well-maintained examples with service records, as these cars respond well to proper care and regular track use.

expertReviews.title: 2025 BMW M2 manual review. Is the M2 one of the last true driver's cars on sale today?
pros: Rare combination of rear-wheel drive, front engine, manual transmission six-cylinder in 2025
Excellent dynamics - predictable, proper muscle, hugely enjoyable to drive
Practical with large boot space and usable rear seats
Distinctive muscular styling that means business
Quick acceleration - 4 seconds 0-60 for manual transmission
Good engine sound and character from straight-six twin turbo
cons: Expensive at £75,000 as tested with many options being extra cost
Heavy at 1,700kg - 200kg heavier than comparable E46 M3
Steering wheel too fat and feels disconnected initially
Track carbon seats interfere with clutch operation due to awkward pedal positioning
Some cheap interior plastics for the price point
Manual transmission is now a £545 extra option
expertReviews.verdict: The M2 represents one of the last true driver's cars available today with its rare combination of manual transmission, rear-wheel drive, and straight-six engine. While it's gotten heavier and more expensive, it delivers excellent dynamics and practicality. The reviewer appreciates BMW continuing to offer this configuration but notes concerns about the high price, weight gain, and some ergonomic issues with the track seats and manual setup.

expertReviews.title: More power! Manual 'box! 2025 BMW M2 review | Autocar
pros: Manual gearbox option with great engagement
Power increase to 473hp with torque available higher in rev range
Improved front-end response and keener turn-in
Excellent traction control with M dynamic mode
High-quality damping that stays connected to road
Can be used as daily driver
cons: Engine sounds industrial and gruff compared to standard B58
Chassis feels stiffer than before when already firm
Pedal positioning issues with carbon bucket seats in RHD
No visual changes to distinguish from previous model
Weighs 1700kg making lightweight seats questionable
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 BMW M2 Competition has evolved into the 480hp rear-wheel-drive coupe it always wanted to be. With subtle but significant chassis improvements including keener front-end response and better rotation, plus the increasingly rare manual gearbox option, it offers excellent daily usability. While the S58 engine lacks the smoothness of BMW's B58 and the car feels stiffer than before, the combination of manual transmission, rear-wheel drive, and strong performance makes it a compelling choice in a shrinking segment.

expertReviews.title: MORE Power! 2025 BMW M2 Review
pros: 473 horsepower from S58 twin-turbo inline-6
Excellent handling and LSD
Good heel-toe capability
Launch control works well
Comfortable seats
Wide body styling has grown on them
cons: Rubbery, poor manual transmission
Weird springy clutch pedal
Suspension too busy and firm even in Comfort
No manual transmission option
$5000 for purple paint
Thick steering wheel
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 BMW M2 Competition offers impressive power and handling with 473 hp, but is held back by transmission issues and overly firm suspension. The manual gearbox feels rubbery with an odd clutch pedal, while the suspension is too busy even in Comfort mode. Performance is strong with good launch control and handling, but the driving experience suffers from these fundamental flaws. Better suited for automatic transmission.

expertReviews.title: 2020 BMW M2 Competition Manual Review - Too Much ...
pros: Incredible straight line acceleration with ~586 wheel horsepower
Engaging manual transmission experience with auto rev match
Good brake performance with upgraded rotors
Sounds great with gruffer exhaust tone
Fun once you adapt to the power delivery
cons: Very traction limited and tail happy
Manual transmission has rubbery feel and grinding issues
Significant turbo lag
Suspension quality not exceptional for the power level
Nerve-wracking to drive with this much power
expertReviews.verdict: This heavily modified M2 Competition with nearly 600 wheel horsepower transforms it into a modern successor to the Mk IV Supra - laggy, explosive power delivery that's thrilling but challenging to manage. While the straight-line performance is incredible, the short wheelbase platform struggles with traction and the manual transmission isn't refined. Needs higher quality suspension and stickier tires to properly handle the power.

expertReviews.title: 2025 BMW M2 Review | Still the Best M Car?
pros: Excellent value at $65-70k starting price
Great one-car solution for daily driving and canyon runs
Natural and linear response compared to other BMW M cars
Comfortable ride quality and supportive carbon bucket seats
S58 engine is talented and rewarding to rev with manual transmission
Short wheelbase provides good steering directness and direction changes
cons: Controversial front bumper design extends 3 inches outward unnecessarily
Heavy tire wear on outer edges of front tires
Manual transmission loses torque (406 lb-ft vs 442 in auto) and fuel economy (22-23 MPG vs high 20s/low 30s)
Less playful and hooligan-like than previous M2 generations
Dead steering feel with minimal feedback
Brake-by-wire system feels spongy with zero pad-on-rotor sensation
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 BMW M2 Competition manual is a surprisingly refined and natural-feeling M car that excels as a one-car solution. While it's less playful than previous generations and has some drawbacks like poor fuel economy and controversial styling, it offers excellent value at $65-70k base price with the M3's S58 engine and gearbox. The reviewer concludes it's the best M car to buy currently, calling it 'a good car' that satisfies both daily driving and spirited canyon runs without major compromises.

expertReviews.title: BMW M2 Competition: Road Review | Carfection 4K
pros: Only costs about £3000 more than standard M2
More sophisticated suspension setup with better bump handling
Progressive rear-wheel drive balance with improved M differential
Proper M engine with 404 horsepower and 460 lb-ft torque
Beautiful carbon brace and improved chassis bracing
More sorted and sophisticated feel compared to previous M2
cons: Engine sounds impressive but lacks character and fizz
Feels somewhat muted and held back compared to potential
Engine doesn't sound as good as the old N55
Could benefit from exhaust remap to unlock more character
expertReviews.verdict: The M2 Competition has come of age with significant suspension improvements that make it feel like a proper M car. While the S55 engine provides more power, it's actually the chassis and handling upgrades that steal the show. The car now handles bumps much better and offers more progressive rear-wheel drive balance. At only £3000 more than the standard M2, it represents excellent value. The suspension changes are the real star, making this a more sophisticated and engaging drive.
